    background-color: #e6f7ff;
    border: 1px solid #ddd;
    padding: 10px;
    margin: 10px 0;
    border-radius: 5px;
    line-height: 1.6;">Length: between a minimum of 1200 words and a maximum of 1600 words. Word count will be a criterion used when determining the grade.<br/><br/>Evidence and Plagiarism: You must directly use the assigned readings by providing quotes to support your analysis. If your paper does not directly use the readings, the most it will earn on the evidence criterion is “Needs Improvement.” When using the readings in your paper, provide citations that include the author, title, and page number. While outside resources can be used, they cannot be used in place of assigned readings. If outside sources are used and not cited, their use will constitute an act of plagiarism, and your paper will earn an automatic zero. It should be noted that I have accounts on all the popular cheating websites and will check those websites if I suspect plagiarism.  <br/><br/>You can use the first person (“I”) in your responses.<br/><br/>The bullet points in the prompts are meant to assist you in developing a thorough answer, but do not offer a bulleted answer in your submission. Be sure to craft cohesive essays where each paragraph transitions smoothly into the next paragraph, making clear that you understand how each aspect of the answer relates to and builds upon each other. :In “On The Value of Philosophy,” Bertrand Russell asserts, “Philosophy, though unable to tell us with certainty what is the true answer to the doubts which it raises, is able to suggest many possibilities which enlarge our thoughts and free them from the tyranny of custom. Thus, while diminishing our feeling of certainty as to what things are, it greatly increases our knowledge as to what they may be; it removes the somewhat arrogant dogmatism of those who have never traveled into the region of liberating doubt, and it keeps alive our sense of wonder by showing familiar things in an unfamiliar aspect” (page 16). Defend this assertion using two philosophers that we have covered since the Mid-Term Exam. Your answer should include the following:<br/><br/>In the opening paragraph, identify the two philosophers you will use in your answer. Furthermore, identify the topics discussed by the philosophers you will address in your response. For example, if you are using Socrates in your answer, you would want to say something along these lines: “I will explain Socrates’s view about the importance of intentions and self-awareness for living an examined life.”<br/>Explain each philosopher’s perspective (ideas, concepts, arguments) on the main topic they discuss in their philosophy, as covered in the lecture and the readings. For example, how does Socrates explain the importance of intentions and self-awareness for living an examined life?<br/>Describe your initial perspective on the topics being discussed.<br/>As a result of exploring the philosophers’ views, explain how your understanding of the topics has changed in the ways that Russell describes in the above quote:<br/>How has your certainty about your own beliefs diminished?<br/>As a result, what questions do you find yourself asking?<br/>How has your sense of the possible answers enlarged?<br/>How does contemplating possible answers spark a sense of wonder about the topics considered?</div><br/><br/>LLM response:<br/><div style="
    background-color: #fff3e6;
    border: 1px solid #ddd;
    padding: 10px;
    margin: 10px 0;
    border-radius: 5px;
    line-height: 1.6;"><p>In his essay “On The Value of Philosophy,” Bertrand Russell argues that philosophy strives towards breaking free from dogmatism, raising doubts about our beliefs, and presenting a multitude of possibilities that can enlarge our thoughts. This not only removes our mistaken arrogance but also enhances our understanding of the world around us, increasing our knowledge. In this essay, I will examine the works of Immanuel Kant and Friedrich Nietzsche and identify how their ideas help strengthen Russell’s argument.</p>
<p>Immanuel Kant is one of the most significant Enlightenment philosophers, known for his contributions to metaphysics, ethics, and epistemology. Kant’s central philosophical concept is the theory of knowledge, where he claims that knowledge is derived from sensory experience and reason. His idea of the “categorical imperative” propagates that moral decisions and actions should be made based on universal principles, treating every individual as an end in themselves rather than as a means to an end. In his Critique of Pure Reason, Kant attempts to resolve the longstanding debate between rationalism and empiricism, arguing that human experience is not enough, and reason is not adequate to understand God, freedom, and immortality. In sharp contrast, human reason is confined only to the finite dimensions of the world and cannot access the infinite realm.</p>
<p>Friedrich Nietzsche, on the other hand, is often criticized for promoting ideas that have been interpreted as nihilistic. He was a profound critic of Christian morality and argued that our values have developed based on conventions, which are subjective and reflective. He believes science and philosophy are antithetical because the former is about explaining the world, while the latter is about interpreting it. Nietzsche argues that human beings must create their values and not rely on the pre-existing ones. He was the first philosopher to announce the death of God, a concept where he contended that religious ideologies had lost their significance in modern-day society. Despite the apparent nihilistic approach, Nietzsche offers his perspective on human flourishing, the overman. Overman represents the pinnacle of human potentials and is the capacity to create new values, paving the way to the transmutation of the common man into the superman.</p>
<p>Initially, I believed that philosophy only focused on abstract arguments that had no real-life applications. However, after reading about Kant's idea of the “categorical imperative” and Nietzsche's “overman,” I have come to understand that philosophy addresses crucial aspects of human life and morality. Both philosophers address the radical human ability to exercise moral agency and the responsibility of making moral decisions independently.</p>
<p>After considering the philosophers’ ideas, my certainty about my beliefs regarding the origin of morality and the role of individuals in them has diminished. I now find myself asking significant and complex questions, such as what defines morality and whether it is objective or subjective. In contemplating possible answers and engaging with philosophical discourse, I have come to develop a more profound appreciation for the diversity of perspectives and the potential implications that individuals and societies have on values, morals, and laws.</p>
<p>By exploring the numerous possibilities that philosophy offers, I find myself liberated from the compulsion to believe only what I have been taught, to question conventional wisdom. Furthermore, examining various philosophical concepts and ideologies has sparked a sense of wonder about the world and the possibilities that await. Philosophy has the power to expand our thinking, allowing us to consider positions and arguments that we would not have contemplated without its influence.</p>
<p>To conclude, the ideas of Kant and Nietzsche serve as an excellent testimony to Russell’s assertion about philosophy. Philosophy encourages us to eschew dogmatism and embrace doubt, leading to the recognition that there is always more than one way to look at something. Engaging with philosophy is not about finding certain answers but expanding our knowledge and understanding of the world, developing thoughtful and meaningful interpretations of the phenomena around us. Through philosophy, we can heighten our sense of wonder about life and the universe.</p></div>

