    border-radius: 5px;
    line-height: 1.6;"><p>Here is an example of an Airflow DAG with a conditional branch:</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">from airflow import DAG
from airflow.operators.dummy_operator import DummyOperator
from airflow.operators.python_operator import PythonOperator
from datetime import datetime

def condition_func(ti):
    x = ti.xcom_pull(task_ids='task1')
    if x &gt; 5:
        return 'branch_a'
    else:
        return 'branch_b'

def task_a():
    print(&quot;Executing branch A&quot;)

def task_b():
    print(&quot;Executing branch B&quot;)

dag = DAG('conditional_branch_dag', start_date=datetime(2021, 1, 1))

start_task = DummyOperator(task_id='start', dag=dag)

task1 = PythonOperator(
    task_id='task1',
    python_callable=lambda: 7,
    dag=dag
)

branch_decision = PythonOperator(
    task_id='branch_decision',
    python_callable=condition_func,
    provide_context=True,
    dag=dag
)

branch_a = PythonOperator(
    task_id='branch_a',
    python_callable=task_a,
    dag=dag
)

branch_b = PythonOperator(
    task_id='branch_b',
    python_callable=task_b,
    dag=dag
)

end_task = DummyOperator(task_id='end', dag=dag)

start_task &gt;&gt; task1 &gt;&gt; branch_decision
branch_decision &gt;&gt; branch_a &gt;&gt; end_task
branch_decision &gt;&gt; branch_b &gt;&gt; end_task
</code></pre>
<p>In this example, we have a DAG named 'conditional_branch_dag' with a start task, 'task1' that calculates a value and pushes it to XCom, and a branch decision task named 'branch_decision' that determines which branch to execute based on the value pulled from XCom.</p>
<p>If the value from 'task1' is greater than 5, it will execute 'branch_a', otherwise it will execute 'branch_b'. Both 'branch_a' and 'branch_b' are PythonOperators that print a message indicating which branch is being executed.</p>
<p>Finally, the 'start_task' is connected to 'task1' and 'branch_decision', and the two branches are connected to the 'end_task' using the <code>&gt;&gt;</code> operator.</p></div>

