 Is<br/>not one that I enjoy. Like I enjoy a lot of other Hindi films like for example<br/>amarak for Anthony. That is one of those films that I can watch anytime and<br/>have a good time. This is not one of those. I don&#x27;t. I don&#x27;t really like it. And I<br/>will tell you guys why or I&#x27;m sure you&#x27;ll figure out throughout this lecture<br/>why. But it&#x27;s a very popular film. It did it really, really well in theaters. And it<br/>came at a time. Again, I said 1994, when a lot of film coming out of the<br/>1980s was very what was called vulgar, which meant there was a lot of<br/>violence. There was a lot of symbolism associated with sex. There was a lot<br/>of sex. That&#x27;s sort of a thing, and it was not necessarily. It was also not<br/>necessarily good films. A lot of 1980s film actually was not was not good<br/>Bollywood film. It was still very, very Bollywood and all of all of its textures,<br/>but it was not. There&#x27;s no Amarok brand, Tony. Let&#x27;s say it was, it was not<br/>70s when it was. It was amazing. But so when this film came out, it came<br/>out at a time when a DVD&#x27;s and VCR and VHS tapes, they were becoming<br/>very popular and when cable TV had become a big force in India. So the<br/>understanding was that Bollywood film was not doing very well because of<br/>these things because people could watch a lot of films at home and<br/>therefore they were not going to theaters. And because of cable TV there<br/>was so much. Availability of entertainment. There was no need to go to the<br/>theaters and watch film, but this film kind of changed that. It was, again, as I<br/>said, it was in theaters forever and it was, it was very, very popular. People<br/>loved this film. So I have here a poster of the phone for you. You have seen<br/>the whole film, but you see that the entire cast, the entire main characters of<br/>the film are on theposter for the film. So it tells us that the film is about<br/>family and the film is about family. That&#x27;s undisputable. Uh, it was made by<br/>Sooraj Barjatya, who has made some of the most popular Bollywood films<br/>again in the history of Hindi cinema. So Hamade Haikan is is one of those<br/>films and another film that he made, this one many APR. Kia was again a<br/>huge blockbuster, played for years and years, and it was a love story<br/>between two people but very strong undercurrents of family and what it<br/>means to be a member of a family. This film hamsat satham. Was it was<br/>100% about family. And these two other films that you see in the bottom of<br/>the screen were also really about family. So we have a theme here. Suraj<br/>Barjatya made films that were about family. Hamat Ki Haikan was kind of<br/>special. It kind of stood out because of the time it came out and because of<br/>what it what it did. So we have we have understood at this point that<br/>Bollywood films have songs. But they have like 5 to 7 songs or five to 8<br/>songs Hommade Haikan and had 14 songs, right? So. It was. It was strange,<br/>but the number of songs there were, but they were all popular. They were all<br/>catchy people. People are still singing them. It was a long film. It is a long<br/>film. Before I forget, I also want to let you know that this film is currently on<br/>Netflix. So if you want to watch it on Netflix, go ahead and go ahead and do<br/>that. If you have a Netflix account. But it&#x27;s also obviously available on the<br/>Secure Media website. You can also watch it there. So back to the film. So it<br/>is a film. That is about family and it became a it came to be understood as a<br/>clean film in that it was about a family, but it was also to be watched with<br/>family. So it was a, it was very family oriented. That was the that was the<br/>goal that that the film was trying to fulfill. Outside of that the message of the<br/>film we don&#x27;t kind it is not a very clear. Message. But if you dig just a bit<br/>deeper, it is very, very there. The film presents a family as if it was the<br/>microcosm for a nation, right? So at the end of the day, this film, like a few<br/>other films that we have seen, is about sacrifice and about sacrifice for<br/>family. But in the clean category, it was very, it was very there, right. There<br/>was no sex in this film. There&#x27;s no violence in this film. It&#x27;s a very, it&#x27;s about a<br/>wedding. A1 wedding happens and then there&#x27;s a huge celebration for the<br/>wedding and the celebration continues to happen for the first hour of the<br/>film. And then the wedding happens and then there&#x27;s post wedding<br/>celebration, then there&#x27;s a childbirth. So there&#x27;s a celebration for that and<br/>there&#x27;s a little bit of tragedy and. And the film again goes on. But in terms of<br/>what the film did for the audience at that time, it was really about. Very kind<br/>of safe entertainment that you could go enjoy with your family which had a<br/>message which showed a family that was a joint family, right. So the idea of<br/>a joint family is multiple generations, at least three, sometimes four living<br/>together and multiple brothers living together. So if there is, you know<br/>parents, parents and there let&#x27;s. Zoom let&#x27;s say three sons and there are<br/>three wives and they&#x27;re, I don&#x27;t know, let&#x27;s say six kids. And sometimes the<br/>kids kids if they&#x27;re that old, but it&#x27;s at least three generations, right? So<br/>grandparents, parents, kids, and then maybe kids, kids, but at least at least<br/>three generations. And that&#x27;s the idea of a joint family. We kind of see that<br/>here, right? So there is the Uber character, Kakaji. And let&#x27;s go back and just<br/>very quickly familiarize ourselves with the characters. So. We have cockatoo<br/>here, and we have his one nephew and his other nephew. So these two<br/>generations are living together. And then we have a little child born. So<br/>that&#x27;s three generations, right? And the third generation is where the film<br/>stops for us, obviously. But in real life, that could be, that could be more. The<br/>other characters are so the brother, the older nephew, marries a girl, her<br/>parents who we see in the top of this, this poster, and then the love interest<br/>of our hero Nisha. And we&#x27;ll talk about all of these characters a little bit<br/>more, but all of these people. So the idea of a joint family, multiple brothers<br/>living together, we see that in this particular film, they&#x27;re living together in<br/>absolute. Probably right. So the idea is not just a joint family, but it is an ideal<br/>joint family. So it is not how families are, but it is how families should be.<br/>And that is kind of what what our author brings us to often in our reading.<br/>So our reading for today is by Patricia Oberoi, and it is entirely the entire<br/>reading is dedicated to this one film. So it gives us a very close. Look at the<br/>phone. The reading is is trying to do three things. So the first thing Patricia<br/>Oberoi does is she explores the idea of family of of this film as being a clean<br/>film and she explores that with actual people, right? So she does interviews<br/>with people in North India. That&#x27;s her first goal. Her second goal is to look at<br/>family as it is on the screen. As a sociologist to kind of see how this thing<br/>operates, right. And the third thing she tries to do or she does in the article is<br/>to tell us how this idea of family can be looked at from a broader perspective,<br/>right? So what does this do for us as viewers and as viewers of Hindi<br/>cinema? So how does this idea of family and this film representing a family?<br/>Fit into our general idea of what India is and what India should be. How does<br/>the idea of family connect to the idea of nation? OK, so these are the three<br/>things, three things that she sets out to do for us. And she does these with<br/>the help of interviews and with the help of people who are who are viewers<br/>of this film, people who have seen this film and who have who have<br/>interacted with film. With this particular film in a in a deeper way&quot;<br/><br/>Using only the lecture content, answer the following question:<br/>&quot;The idealized version of a joint family, at least as told in Hum Aapke Hain Kaun, is that the individual sacrifices for the betterment of the family as a whole. How does this fit into family as a microcosm of the nation.&quot; Make it a 200 word response</div><br/><br/>LLM response:<br/><div style="
    background-color: #fff3e6;
    border: 1px solid #ddd;
    padding: 10px;
    margin: 10px 0;
    border-radius: 5px;
    line-height: 1.6;"><p>The idealized portrayal of a joint family in "Hum Aapke Hain Kaun" (HAHK), where individual sacrifice is glorified for the family's collective good, aligns with the notion of family as a microcosm for the nation in several ways. In this depiction, the family unit embodies the broader national values of unity, collective responsibility, and cohesive living, mirroring how citizens might ideally come together for the benefit of the country as a whole.</p>
<p>Just as individuals in HAHK suppress their personal desires to maintain harmony and prosperity within the family, citizens are often called upon to prioritize national interests over their own. The narrative of HAHK, wherein the family operates through consensus and cooperation, reflects aspirations for national identity—where citizens work jointly towards nation-building efforts, bolstered by a shared sense of purpose and belonging.</p>
<p>HAHK extends the metaphor of family as nation by emphasizing the importance of continuity and tradition, much like national pride is rooted in historical and cultural legacy. The way the characters in HAHK uphold family honor and legacy parallels how a nation's citizens may uphold and honor their country's heritage and principles.</p>
<p>Overall, the representation of the joint family in HAHK as an epitome of sacrifice and collective well-being exemplifies the Indian ideal of nationhood, one in which the integrity of the community supersedes individualism—just as the welfare of the nation transcends individual aspirations. The film thus uses the family narrative as a vehicle to promote and reflect broader social and national ideals.</p></div>

