    margin: 10px 0;
    border-radius: 5px;
    line-height: 1.6;">Why would i be called &quot;shit&quot; if i got kicked from my crew for accepting a ranked 3v3. by someone.</div><br/><br/>LLM response:<br/><div style="
    background-color: #fff3e6;
    border: 1px solid #ddd;
    padding: 10px;
    margin: 10px 0;
    border-radius: 5px;
    line-height: 1.6;"><p>Being called "shit" or other derogatory terms by someone, especially after being kicked out of a gaming crew or team, can be a harsh and unpleasant experience. This scenario could unfold for several reasons, most revolving around community dynamics, expectations, and gaming culture.</p>
<ol>
<li>
<p><strong>Perceived Betrayal or Disloyalty</strong>: In tightly-knit gaming communities, especially competitive ones, there's often an unspoken rule about loyalty and prioritizing the team's needs. If you accepted a ranked 3v3 match (possibly with members from another team or players considered to be of a lower skill level), your crew might see this as a betrayal of their trust, especially if the action was against the crew's strategy or rules.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Expectation vs. Action</strong>: Teams, especially those in competitive scenes, may have explicit or implicit expectations about how members should behave, including whom they should play with and what types of games or matches they should engage in. By accepting the ranked 3v3, you might have inadvertently signaled that you do not share the team's values or goals, prompting a negative reaction.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Toxic Gaming Culture</strong>: Unfortunately, the gaming world can sometimes foster a toxic environment where insults and derogatory language are used too freely. Such environments can amplify negative reactions to misunderstandings or perceived slights, leading to harsh words or actions that wouldn't be considered reasonable or acceptable in real-world social interactions.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Scapegoating</strong>: In some instances, teams might look for someone to blame for recent poor performances, internal conflicts, or a general atmosphere of dissatisfaction. Your actions could have been used as a pretext to kick you out, with the insult adding injury to insult, so to speak.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Ego and Competition</strong>: Competitive environments, especially in gaming, can sometimes bring out the worst in people. Being called "shit" might have more to do with the other person's ego, insecurities, or competitive nature than your actual skills or the appropriateness of your actions.</p>
</li>
</ol>
<p>It's important to remember that being called derogatory names reflects more on the person using them than on you. Gaming should be about enjoyment, improvement, and camaraderie. If you find yourself ousted from a group that doesn't respect you or treat you well, it may be an opportunity to find a new crew that values you more and aligns better with your own gaming philosophy and personal values.</p></div>

